<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="495" pageId="0" pageNumber="494" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1939,2036]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="495" pageId="0" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1939,1964]" pageId="0" pageNumber="494">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Body color yellowish, greenish or brownish. Body small, slender; head usually as wide as pronotum, sometimes narrower or slightly wider; crown very short, anterior margin weakly angulate, usually parallel to hind margin; rostrum with apical segment short. Forewings elongate, with two subapical cells. Hindwings with three apical cells. Hind tibia pecten with two transverse rows of setae; first tarsomere pecten with inner acute seta much longer than adjacent platellae. Style with apical process usually strongly arched; lateral lobe well-developed, rarely reduced; basal arms short. Aedeagal shaft usually simple, tubular, recurved anterodorsally, base sometimes expanded in lateral view; rarely with process, if present basal. Macrosetae of pygofer and subgenital plate plumose.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
